  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improved Sanitation and Waste Management for Rohingya Camps and Host Communities in Bangladesh</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Due to the Rohingya refugee influx from Rakhine State in Myanmar to the Cox&#x2019;s Bazar District of Bangladesh in August 2017, the population of two upazilas (Ukhiya and Teknaf) located in the southern part of the Cox&#x2019;s Bazar district, has grown to approximately 1.5 million people. This has significantly complicated existing sanitation challenges. It is estimated that over 10,000 tons (approximately 22,000m3) of waste is produced per month in the two upazilas, both of which lack a functioning solid waste management system and for which no land is currently available. The project focuses on life-saving activities through sanitation maintenance, decentralized faecal sludge treatment, localized solid-waste management and improved drainage systems in the refugee camp and identified adjacent host communities in Ukhiya Upazila. The proposed response improves IOM operations by continuing water, sanitation and hygiene, site management and site development, and protection services in targeted refugee camps and communities using existing and proposed interventions.</narrative>
  </description>
